Package com.atakmap.lang

Class Unsafe

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.atakmap.lang.Unsafe
  • public final class Unsafe
extends java.lang.Object
    Static utility functions for working with native memory. Many methods are unchecked and may perform significantly faster than comparable methods on direct Buffer objects. Unless specified otherwise, byte order should always be considered to be in native order.

    The methods in this class work directly with native memory and are considered unsafe. Incorrect use of the methods in this class can produce unpredictable results and may result in crashing the application.

        public static long allocate​(int size)
        Allocates a block of memory. Memory allocated using this method should always be freed using free(long).
        Parameters:
        size - The size to allocate, in bytes.
        Returns:
        The pointer to the allocated memory.

      • free

        public static void free​(long pointer)
        Frees the previously allocated block of memory. This method should only be used to free memory allocated by allocate(int).
        Parameters:
        pointer - The pointer to the memory.

      • allocateDirect

        public static java.nio.ByteBuffer allocateDirect​(int capacity)
        Allocates a new ByteBuffer that is backed by a block of native memory. As opposed to ByteBuffer.allocateDirect(int), this method may be able to do its allocation in such a way that it does not count towards the JVM heap space.
        Parameters:
        capacity - The desired capacity in bytes.
        Returns:
        The direct allocated ByteBuffer. There is no need to explicitly free the returned object.
        See Also:
        ByteBuffer.allocateDirect(int)

      • free

        public static void free​(java.nio.Buffer buffer)
        Attempts to free the native memory associated with an NIO Buffer allocated via or derived from a ByteBuffer allocated via ByteBuffer.allocateDirect(int). While there is no guarantee that this method will succeed, the caller should take care not to invoke any methods on the provided buffer after the method returns.
        Parameters:
        buffer - A Buffer previously allocated via or derived from a ByteBuffer allocated via ByteBuffer.allocateDirect(int).
